            "id": "q-hs-tr-1",
            "type": "single",
            "question": "What does an RSI reading above 70 indicate?",
            "options": [
              {
                "label": "The asset is a strong buy",
                "value": "A"
              },
              {
                "label": "The asset is overbought — a pullback may be coming",
                "value": "B"
              },
              {
                "label": "The trading volume is very high",
                "value": "C"
              },
              {
                "label": "A bullish MACD crossover has occurred",
                "value": "D"
              }
            ],
            "answer": [
              "B"
            ],
            "analysis": "RSI above 70 means the asset has gained significantly in a short period and may be due for a pullback — it's 'overbought' relative to recent price history. However, in strong uptrends, RSI can stay above 70 for extended periods. Always wait for RSI to turn before acting on it.",
            "points": 1
          },
          {
            "id": "q-hs-tr-2",
            "type": "single",
            "question": "What is 'role reversal' in support and resistance?",
            "options": [
              {
                "label": "When buyers and sellers switch roles",
                "value": "A"
              },
              {
                "label": "When a resistance level, once broken, becomes the new support",
                "value": "B"
              },
              {
                "label": "When a chart pattern reverses direction",
                "value": "C"
              },
              {
                "label": "When RSI moves from overbought to oversold",
                "value": "D"
              }
            ],
            "answer": [
              "B"
            ],
            "analysis": "Role reversal: when price breaks convincingly above a resistance level, that level often becomes the new support on a pullback. Old resistance becomes new support (and vice versa). Traders use retests of these flipped levels for high-probability entries.",
            "points": 1
          },
          {
            "id": "q-hs-tr-3",
            "type": "single",
            "question": "What is the difference between a limit order and a market order?",
            "options": [
              {
                "label": "Market orders are only available on CEXs; limit orders only on DEXs",
                "value": "A"
              },
              {
                "label": "A market order executes immediately at current price; a limit order only fills at your specified price or better",
                "value": "B"
              },
              {
                "label": "Limit orders always fill faster than market orders",
                "value": "C"
              },
              {
                "label": "Market orders require more collateral",
                "value": "D"
              }
            ],
            "answer": [
              "B"
            ],
            "analysis": "A market order executes immediately at whatever the best available price is — guaranteed to fill. A limit order specifies the maximum price you'll pay (or minimum you'll sell for) — it only fills if the market reaches that level, giving you price control but no fill guarantee.",
            "points": 1
          },
          {
            "id": "q-hs-tr-4",
            "type": "single",
            "question": "What is 'FOMO' in trading?",
            "options": [
              {
                "label": "A type of chart pattern",
                "value": "A"
              },
              {
                "label": "Fear of Missing Out — buying into a move after it's already happened, often near the top",
